REBUT: The opponent claims the FMix effectiveness is "[WEAK]" because they suspect "spectral bias overfitting" (the model might learn to rely on the Fourier signature of the masks). This ignores the fundamental decoupling provided by the FMix mechanism. In CutMix, the rectangular geometry is a high-frequency, non-natural artifact that is easy for a CNN to "memorize" as a feature. FMix, by using low-frequency Fourier sampling, specifically *removes* these high-frequency structural artifacts. The paper's MI evidence ($I(Z_{FMix}; X) > I(Z_{CutMix}; X)$) proves that FMix preserves more of the original data's characteristic information. The "complexity" of the mask is precisely what prevents the model from overfitting to the mask itself, as the mask's boundaries are no longer predictable, rectangular primitives.

